Monk and Conrad provided a great list! 

I am personally excited to be surprised üòÖ Energy seems to be flowing back into our space, and I think it will lead to innovations that help bring digital art to the wider public.

Definitely. The logical step would be to open one permanent location at some point, mimicking what traditional art institutions do, but the digital nature of our collection allows us to be more experimental. It‚Äôs inspiring to see what Bright Moments has been doing, and where one can go from there.

Procedural generative art feels limited/forced when used for figurative expression to me. AI seems to be a natural fit here. 

So I see procedural and AI as great complements for artists interested in computation. 

At Le Random, we are definitely fascinated by both!
What are you excited for in 2024? :)
Ahhh great question! According to the most popular definition, collections such as CryptoPunks and Bored Apes are definitely generative in nature. But whether they are art, is a different question :)
I think it‚Äôs important to stress that generative art is a very expansive category, going beyond the digital world, and one needs to define what part (if any) speaks to them.

I have some thoughts on the market structure. So many improvements needed to truly unlock the democratising potential of digital art.

Once the structure has drastically improved, the state of the market will do so too. 

But people seem to wait for a better market to devote their careers to digital art ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

Let me guess: AI to absorb procedural? üëÄ

What do you think will happen to the term ‚ÄúAI art(ist)‚Äù when AI technology is embedded in all popular image making tools? Do you think it will always be a thing?
